Movie: How to Blow Up a Pipeline

Review: If you’re going to make a movie about a self-insert protagonist who is always the kindest, funniest, most charming person in the room, at least spare us the coming-of-age/early-adulthood-is-so-hard framing.

Minute to minute this is one of the best procedural thrillers of all time, and that's maybe the least impressive thing about it. Every frame is perfectly composed. The blocking is effortless -- watching characters move fluidly in and out of gorgeous tableaus for the entire runtime of the film is magical. It's got something on it's mind; this is a story about a man who weighs the life of a child against his fortune while his adversary watches from the literal depths below. And it's not didactic: the film's ideas are cleanly woven through its genre construction.
